00:02:34.820 --> 00:02:39.590
So the Hotelling decision,
the Hotelling theory,

00:02:39.590 --> 00:02:42.360
is pretty straightforward.

00:02:42.360 --> 00:02:46.700
You imagine you have 1,000
barrels of oil in the ground.

00:02:46.700 --> 00:02:47.690
You have a valve.

00:02:47.690 --> 00:02:50.210
You can pump it out whenever
you choose to pump it out.

00:02:50.210 --> 00:02:54.720
It costs you $30 a
barrel to pump it out.

00:02:54.720 --> 00:02:57.140
And you can produce
it whenever you want.

00:02:57.140 --> 00:03:00.050
The price of oil
today is $80 a barrel.

00:03:00.050 --> 00:03:05.640
If you know the future,
this theory says,

00:03:05.640 --> 00:03:08.040
how do you decide
when to produce?

00:03:08.040 --> 00:03:09.037
Brendan.

00:03:09.037 --> 00:03:10.985
AUDIENCE: You just
choose the days

00:03:10.985 --> 00:03:13.907
when the oil prices are
the highest per barrel.

00:03:13.907 --> 00:03:16.178
I mean, the oil per barrel
price is the highest.

00:03:16.178 --> 00:03:18.220
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: You
want to discount, maybe?

00:03:18.220 --> 00:03:19.260
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:03:19.260 --> 00:03:20.635
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
So you might

00:03:20.635 --> 00:03:24.520
want to maximize
discounted net revenue.

00:03:24.520 --> 00:03:27.160
Marginal cost is the
same, by assumption.

00:03:27.160 --> 00:03:29.440
So yeah, you'd want
to maximize that.

00:03:29.440 --> 00:03:32.430
So you choose a time T or a
set of T's, if they're are all

00:03:32.430 --> 00:03:35.150
equivalent, and pump it out.

00:03:35.150 --> 00:03:36.570
Is that clear?

00:03:36.570 --> 00:03:38.310
That's sort of how you decide.

00:03:38.310 --> 00:03:40.320
You've got a choice of time now.

00:03:40.320 --> 00:03:41.788
So you look period by period.

00:03:41.788 --> 00:03:43.080
You say, when is the good time?

00:03:43.080 --> 00:03:45.550
You'd pump it out then.

00:03:45.550 --> 00:03:48.570
Now, the interesting
question is,

00:03:48.570 --> 00:03:51.100
suppose the whole
world looks like this.

00:03:51.100 --> 00:03:56.610
Suppose everybody's got an
oil well exactly like yours.

00:03:56.610 --> 00:03:58.590
What has to happen
to the price of oil?

00:04:03.400 --> 00:04:05.410
Kirsten, want to take a shot?

00:04:05.410 --> 00:04:09.010
What's the price
of oil have to do?

00:04:09.010 --> 00:04:12.160
AUDIENCE: It has to
respond to demand.

00:04:12.160 --> 00:04:14.050
If all the oil wells
are exactly the same,

00:04:14.050 --> 00:04:15.876
then you're assuming
that [INAUDIBLE]..

00:04:15.876 --> 00:04:17.709
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Well, I'm sitting here.

00:04:17.709 --> 00:04:21.067
I have 1,000 barrels
in the ground.

00:04:21.067 --> 00:04:22.900
Everybody's got 1,000
barrels in the ground.

00:04:22.900 --> 00:04:26.890
There are a lot of us,
so it's competitive.

00:04:26.890 --> 00:04:28.660
And I have perfect foresight.

00:04:28.660 --> 00:04:31.490
I can see where the
price of oil is going.

00:04:31.490 --> 00:04:36.290
So if that market with
all of us with wells

00:04:36.290 --> 00:04:39.680
like that and a known
demand curve, let's say,

00:04:39.680 --> 00:04:44.690
is going to be in equilibrium,
what has to happen to price?

00:04:44.690 --> 00:04:46.480
OK, let me push
you a little bit.

00:04:46.480 --> 00:04:48.530
Suppose the price today--

00:04:48.530 --> 00:04:57.050
suppose it's two periods,
and call that thing up there

00:04:57.050 --> 00:04:59.720
"discounted net price."

00:04:59.720 --> 00:05:02.690
Suppose discounted net
price today is higher than

00:05:02.690 --> 00:05:04.130
discounted net price tomorrow.

00:05:04.130 --> 00:05:05.470
When do I produce?

00:05:05.470 --> 00:05:06.305
AUDIENCE: Today.

00:05:06.305 --> 00:05:07.430
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Today.

00:05:07.430 --> 00:05:09.320
And if we're
identical and we all

00:05:09.320 --> 00:05:12.810
produce today, what
happens to today's price?

00:05:12.810 --> 00:05:13.730
AUDIENCE: Goes down.

00:05:13.730 --> 00:05:15.440
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Goes down,
so it probably isn't going

00:05:15.440 --> 00:05:17.180
to be higher than tomorrow's.

00:05:17.180 --> 00:05:20.240
Suppose it's lower
than tomorrow's.

00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:21.110
What do we all do?

00:05:21.110 --> 00:05:22.318
AUDIENCE: Wait till tomorrow.

00:05:22.318 --> 00:05:24.027
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
And if we all wait--

00:05:24.027 --> 00:05:25.200
AUDIENCE: Then it goes down.

00:05:25.200 --> 00:05:26.700
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
If we all wait,

00:05:26.700 --> 00:05:29.750
then today's price goes up,
because nobody's producing.

00:05:29.750 --> 00:05:33.080
If it's equal to
tomorrow's, then we sort of

00:05:33.080 --> 00:05:36.500
don't care when we produce.

00:05:36.500 --> 00:05:39.560
And it kind of can be
in equilibrium then,

00:05:39.560 --> 00:05:40.728
if it's equal.

00:05:40.728 --> 00:05:42.770
But if it's not equal, it
can't be an equilibrium

00:05:42.770 --> 00:05:45.950
between the two days.

00:05:45.950 --> 00:05:47.330
Everybody see that?

00:05:47.330 --> 00:05:51.500
If the discounted net price
is different in two periods,

00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:54.800
it can't be in equilibrium,
because either you'll

00:05:54.800 --> 00:05:57.810
switch out of one or you'll
switch into the other,

00:05:57.810 --> 00:06:00.150
and that'll upset the price.

00:06:00.150 --> 00:06:05.780
So if today's price is low,
if I expect the price to rise

00:06:05.780 --> 00:06:09.050
rapidly, I won't produce.

00:06:09.050 --> 00:06:10.790
Neither will anybody else.

00:06:10.790 --> 00:06:13.700
Today's price won't be
low if nobody's producing.

00:06:13.700 --> 00:06:15.770
That's not an equilibrium.

00:06:15.770 --> 00:06:19.520
If today's price is high
relative to my expectations

00:06:19.520 --> 00:06:22.350
tomorrow, I'm going to produce.

00:06:22.350 --> 00:06:25.980
And if we all produce,
it can't stay high.

00:06:25.980 --> 00:06:29.240
The only way you can
have an equilibrium

00:06:29.240 --> 00:06:34.730
is if this quantity,
price minus marginal cost,

00:06:34.730 --> 00:06:37.680
rises at the rate of interest.

00:06:37.680 --> 00:06:40.190
If that rises at the
rate of interest,

00:06:40.190 --> 00:06:42.050
then I don't care
when I produce.

00:06:45.060 --> 00:06:48.120
Basically the other way to
think about it, that I think

00:06:48.120 --> 00:06:50.310
maybe is the most
useful, is I've

00:06:50.310 --> 00:06:56.040
got a choice between leaving
the oil in the ground

00:06:56.040 --> 00:06:58.980
and leaving my
money in the bank,

00:06:58.980 --> 00:07:04.950
hypothetically getting
interest rate R. Sorry,

00:07:04.950 --> 00:07:07.830
I have a choice between
leaving the oil in the ground

00:07:07.830 --> 00:07:13.590
and getting whatever I get based
on the future price of oil,

00:07:13.590 --> 00:07:16.590
or pumping the oil out and
putting the money in the bank.

00:07:16.590 --> 00:07:19.980
So I can either invest
in oil or in the bank.

00:07:19.980 --> 00:07:25.470
And unless those two are equal,
I won't be in equilibrium.

00:07:25.470 --> 00:07:28.860
And the mechanism I went
through with Kirsten

00:07:28.860 --> 00:07:36.000
is if you're out of equilibrium,
if this equality doesn't hold

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:43.290
for all t, then we will, all
of us in a competitive market,

00:07:43.290 --> 00:07:47.340
make changes in production
decisions that move you

00:07:47.340 --> 00:07:49.920
in the direction of equilibrium.

00:07:49.920 --> 00:07:57.050
So if tomorrow's price is
low relative to today's, we

00:07:57.050 --> 00:07:59.760
produce today, which
lowers today's prices,

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:02.330
so that can't be an equilibrium.

00:08:02.330 --> 00:08:06.680
If today's price is low
relative to tomorrow,

00:08:06.680 --> 00:08:09.860
we all wait, which
raises today's price.

00:08:09.860 --> 00:08:14.510
Only if that equality
holds do we not

00:08:14.510 --> 00:08:17.835
have an incentive, all of us, to
shift production dramatically.

00:08:20.490 --> 00:08:21.570
So it's investing.

00:08:21.570 --> 00:08:23.490
It's leaving it in the
oil versus leaving it

00:08:23.490 --> 00:08:25.530
in the ground versus
putting it in the bank.

00:08:25.530 --> 00:08:27.765
If those two aren't
equal, you readjust.

00:08:32.190 --> 00:08:37.340
Is that pretty
straightforward at this stage?

00:08:37.340 --> 00:08:40.909
OK, one thing that's
interesting about this story

00:08:40.909 --> 00:08:43.789
is you'll notice that price
is above marginal cost

00:08:43.789 --> 00:08:47.740
everywhere, even though
by assumption it's

00:08:47.740 --> 00:08:50.820
a competitive market.

00:08:50.820 --> 00:08:52.780
How can that be?

00:08:52.780 --> 00:08:58.290
Well, that's because
when you produce today,

00:08:58.290 --> 00:09:00.780
you incur not only the
marginal production costs,

00:09:00.780 --> 00:09:04.350
but you incur an
opportunity cost.

00:09:04.350 --> 00:09:07.500
With only 1,000 barrels,
if I produce today,

00:09:07.500 --> 00:09:12.080
I lose the chance of producing
that barrel in the future.

00:09:12.080 --> 00:09:16.600
So part of the cost
of producing today

00:09:16.600 --> 00:09:19.660
is that opportunity cost, which
is why the equilibrium has

00:09:19.660 --> 00:09:21.980
price above marginal cost.

00:09:21.980 --> 00:09:26.650
If price is equal to
marginal cost at all times,

00:09:26.650 --> 00:09:29.110
nobody's going to produce.

00:09:29.110 --> 00:09:32.140
Why would I produce today, given
that prices might be better

00:09:32.140 --> 00:09:34.370
tomorrow, blah, blah, blah?

00:09:34.370 --> 00:09:39.210
So that's the basic
Hotelling story--

00:09:39.210 --> 00:09:41.280
that under competitive
conditions,

00:09:41.280 --> 00:09:43.810
price rises at the
rate of interest.

00:09:43.810 --> 00:09:47.370
This is the usual
picture with time.

00:09:47.370 --> 00:09:49.980
Price minus marginal
cost rises at the rate

00:09:49.980 --> 00:09:53.610
of interest or simply enough--

00:09:53.610 --> 00:09:56.280
with the given
demand curve, you're

00:09:56.280 --> 00:09:58.110
basically running
up the demand curve

00:09:58.110 --> 00:10:01.150
until you run out
of whatever it is.

00:10:01.150 --> 00:10:05.570
And this has quantity on the
axis and this time on the axis,

00:10:05.570 --> 00:10:08.380
so that you can't go immediately
from one to the other,

00:10:08.380 --> 00:10:10.960
but you see the point.

00:10:10.960 --> 00:10:13.610
And for simple cases, you
can just write it out.

00:10:13.610 --> 00:10:16.787
You can solve the equations.

00:10:16.787 --> 00:10:18.370
So under these
assumptions, it doesn't

00:10:18.370 --> 00:10:20.078
matter when you produce
the oil if you're

00:10:20.078 --> 00:10:22.720
a competitor, because
all these have

00:10:22.720 --> 00:10:25.920
the same discounted net revenue.

00:10:25.920 --> 00:10:30.360
And if a monopoly has all the
oil and you're a competitor,

00:10:30.360 --> 00:10:32.160
you might want to
produce now because what

00:10:32.160 --> 00:10:34.710
the monopolist will do
will have marginal revenue

00:10:34.710 --> 00:10:37.480
minus marginal cost rise
at the interest rate.

00:10:37.480 --> 00:10:39.980
And if that doesn't make sense
to you, don't worry about it.

00:10:39.980 --> 00:10:43.000
We're not coming back to it.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:45.040
So you may want
to produce today.

00:10:45.040 --> 00:10:48.070
Now, this is a
really nice theory.

00:10:48.070 --> 00:10:49.300
This is very elegant.

00:10:49.300 --> 00:10:50.560
It's very simple.

00:10:50.560 --> 00:10:52.690
I didn't have to wave
my hands too rapidly,

00:10:52.690 --> 00:10:54.650
I think, to explain it.

00:10:54.650 --> 00:10:57.790
There's only one tiny
problem with it--

00:10:57.790 --> 00:11:01.170
prices don't rise at
the rate of interest.

00:11:01.170 --> 00:11:03.460
These are oil prices.

00:11:03.460 --> 00:11:06.850
These are 2010 dollars,
so the lighter line

00:11:06.850 --> 00:11:08.230
is the real price of oil.

00:11:08.230 --> 00:11:11.290
And that is not a smooth curve
rising at the rate of interest

00:11:11.290 --> 00:11:14.090
at any time in any place.

00:11:14.090 --> 00:11:16.090
So the first thing
you have to ask

00:11:16.090 --> 00:11:22.690
is, is that theory fundamentally
crazy or is it too simplified

00:11:22.690 --> 00:11:24.530
by a bit?

00:11:24.530 --> 00:11:28.410
And the answer is, I
think, it's too simplified.

00:11:28.410 --> 00:11:33.120
And I'm going to talk a little
bit about what it leaves out,

00:11:33.120 --> 00:11:38.680
without trying to do anything
more complex than that.

00:11:38.680 --> 00:11:40.725
It's important.

00:11:40.725 --> 00:11:42.600
So there are a bunch of
things it leaves out.

00:11:42.600 --> 00:11:47.100
I think the most important
one is exploration,

00:11:47.100 --> 00:11:51.700
because you don't have 1,000
barrels in your well ever.

00:11:51.700 --> 00:11:55.920
You don't know what you've got.

00:11:55.920 --> 00:11:59.400
If you think about--
just focus on oil--

00:11:59.400 --> 00:12:02.670
you look for promising geology.

00:12:02.670 --> 00:12:05.070
You explore it.

00:12:05.070 --> 00:12:07.650
You drill to prove the reserves.

00:12:07.650 --> 00:12:11.700
You refine your estimates.

00:12:11.700 --> 00:12:15.330
A former teacher of mine
just said Hotelling is wrong.

00:12:15.330 --> 00:12:19.650
It's not a tank of
oil, it's an inventory.

00:12:19.650 --> 00:12:21.920
As an oil company,
you build inventory,

00:12:21.920 --> 00:12:24.370
and then you run down inventory.

00:12:24.370 --> 00:12:29.090
So reserves at any time are the
result of a set of decisions.

00:12:29.090 --> 00:12:32.200
But the decisions have
this same dimension.

00:12:32.200 --> 00:12:34.540
When do you explore?

00:12:34.540 --> 00:12:36.250
When do you invest?

00:12:36.250 --> 00:12:39.250
When do you lease a tract?

00:12:39.250 --> 00:12:40.450
When do you drill?

00:12:40.450 --> 00:12:41.920
How many wells do you drill?

00:12:41.920 --> 00:12:44.380
Those are all when decisions.

00:12:44.380 --> 00:12:46.810
Those are all
intratemporal decisions.

00:12:46.810 --> 00:12:50.500
And you have to think about
today's price and tomorrow's

00:12:50.500 --> 00:12:51.700
price.

00:12:51.700 --> 00:12:53.800
And if you think today's
price is really low

00:12:53.800 --> 00:12:56.940
and tomorrow's price is
going to be better, you wait.

00:12:56.940 --> 00:12:59.010
If you think today's
prices are high

00:12:59.010 --> 00:13:03.460
and you can get the oil out
in a hurry, you move ahead.

00:13:03.460 --> 00:13:09.280
So this same notion that's
in the simple model, that

00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:11.650
says I've got to think
about the path of price

00:13:11.650 --> 00:13:14.170
to make decisions,
holds true, but these

00:13:14.170 --> 00:13:17.720
are much more
complicated decisions.

00:13:17.720 --> 00:13:21.710
and in the face of uncertainty,
because you don't really

00:13:21.710 --> 00:13:26.420
know reserves or demand
or anything else.

00:13:26.420 --> 00:13:31.100
And interesting little number--

00:13:31.100 --> 00:13:35.810
from proved reserves, you
can look up a definition,

00:13:35.810 --> 00:13:38.990
but it means reasonably likely
you can get that oil out

00:13:38.990 --> 00:13:41.510
at commercial costs.

00:13:41.510 --> 00:13:45.680
So from the end of 1976
to the end of 2009,

00:13:45.680 --> 00:13:52.550
proved oil reserves in the US
fell by 10.26 billion barrels.

00:13:52.550 --> 00:13:56.710
How much do you think was
produced over that period?

00:13:56.710 --> 00:14:00.830
How many of you think more
than 20 billion barrels

00:14:00.830 --> 00:14:02.750
was produced over that period?

00:14:02.750 --> 00:14:06.260
Reserves fell by 10.26.

00:14:06.260 --> 00:14:08.510
How many think that over
that period, more than 20

00:14:08.510 --> 00:14:11.330
were produced?

00:14:11.330 --> 00:14:12.950
OK, how many over 30?

00:14:16.290 --> 00:14:17.610
Anybody think over 40?

