in 2008, I guess,

00:27:51.730 --> 00:27:53.230
or 2007, whichever
one that hit in.

00:27:53.230 --> 00:27:55.420
I forget.

00:27:55.420 --> 00:27:58.180
That's just remarkably volatile.

00:27:58.180 --> 00:27:59.980
This one we understand.

00:27:59.980 --> 00:28:00.940
That was politics.

00:28:00.940 --> 00:28:03.100
That was a huge supply cut.

00:28:03.100 --> 00:28:07.840
This appears to be a
significant, unanticipated

00:28:07.840 --> 00:28:11.350
increase in demand with very
inelastic short-run supply.

00:28:11.350 --> 00:28:14.070
But it is still being debated.

00:28:14.070 --> 00:28:16.700
There are people who say,
well that must be speculation.

00:28:16.700 --> 00:28:19.160
And you say, well, yeah,
but if you bought oil

00:28:19.160 --> 00:28:21.830
at those high prices,
you took delivery.

00:28:21.830 --> 00:28:23.690
People actually got the stuff.

00:28:23.690 --> 00:28:26.810
People were taking
delivery at these prices.

00:28:26.810 --> 00:28:27.650
That isn't paper.

00:28:27.650 --> 00:28:29.870
That's barrels of oil
coming off a tanker.

00:28:29.870 --> 00:28:35.210
So it's hard to tell a
speculative story, I think.

00:28:35.210 --> 00:28:37.357
I think it's supply
and demand, but you're

00:28:37.357 --> 00:28:39.440
right-- that's just that's
as volatile as anything

00:28:39.440 --> 00:28:41.060
you're ever going to see.

00:28:41.060 --> 00:28:43.850
And nobody expects
volatility to go back

00:28:43.850 --> 00:28:48.050
to all these good, old days
because the politics haven't

00:28:48.050 --> 00:28:50.280
gotten any simpler.

00:28:50.280 --> 00:28:55.020
If there is a war in Iran, you
will see a heck of a spike.

00:28:55.020 --> 00:28:58.530
And in fact, we and the
Europeans and others

00:28:58.530 --> 00:29:01.440
are in the process of putting
sanctions on Iran designed

00:29:01.440 --> 00:29:03.480
to limit their exports.

00:29:03.480 --> 00:29:06.030
Well, if the Saudis
don't pick up the slack,

00:29:06.030 --> 00:29:07.680
we'll see another spike.

00:29:07.680 --> 00:29:09.220
We'll see.

00:29:09.220 --> 00:29:10.315
Anything else?

00:29:10.315 --> 00:29:13.777
AUDIENCE: So the cost of
production was $3, $4?

00:29:13.777 --> 00:29:15.610
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
I'm making up a number,

00:29:15.610 --> 00:29:17.485
but the cost of production
in the Middle East

00:29:17.485 --> 00:29:19.510
is well below the market price.

00:29:19.510 --> 00:29:21.640
AUDIENCE: And I'm just
wondering if it's $5,

00:29:21.640 --> 00:29:27.193
and the cost of a barrel
of oil is $100 [INAUDIBLE]..

00:29:27.193 --> 00:29:29.110
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Well, remember, the price

00:29:29.110 --> 00:29:31.068
is always going to be
above marginal production

00:29:31.068 --> 00:29:34.220
cost because of the
opportunity cost argument.

00:29:34.220 --> 00:29:37.090
So that's not a big surprise.

00:29:37.090 --> 00:29:42.130
And the low-cost producers
in the Middle East

00:29:42.130 --> 00:29:45.220
are not behaving like
pure competitors.

00:29:45.220 --> 00:29:47.240
They're restricting output.

00:29:47.240 --> 00:29:49.390
So yeah, there was a time
when the price of oil

00:29:49.390 --> 00:29:50.650
was, I don't know--

00:29:50.650 --> 00:29:56.110
well, look here-- when the price
of oil in the '73 shock went up

00:29:56.110 --> 00:29:58.440
to-- and I think it--

00:29:58.440 --> 00:30:00.570
I can't quite read this.

00:30:00.570 --> 00:30:06.270
Oh, this is some sort of blended
price, which I don't quite get.

00:30:06.270 --> 00:30:08.850
But the price of oil quadrupled.

00:30:08.850 --> 00:30:10.410
The cost of oil
didn't quadruple.

00:30:10.410 --> 00:30:13.060
And it stayed high.

00:30:13.060 --> 00:30:16.230
Look at the money of the day,
which is where we all live.

00:30:16.230 --> 00:30:18.905
It went up dramatically.

00:30:18.905 --> 00:30:20.280
Oh, you know what
the problem is?

00:30:20.280 --> 00:30:22.740
I think this is in--

00:30:22.740 --> 00:30:24.920
what is it dollars per--
yes, I never understood.

00:30:24.920 --> 00:30:25.920
No, it's per barrel, OK.

00:30:25.920 --> 00:30:28.350
I thought it was per
ton of oil equivalent.

00:30:28.350 --> 00:30:34.280
But the price quadrupled
in a few months.

00:30:34.280 --> 00:30:35.930
And the cost didn't.

00:30:35.930 --> 00:30:38.690
That was pure market power.

00:30:38.690 --> 00:30:42.500
And if they were making
money at these prices,

00:30:42.500 --> 00:30:45.660
they were making a lot
of money at those prices.

00:30:45.660 --> 00:30:48.300
The journals were full of
articles about recycling

00:30:48.300 --> 00:30:50.160
petrodollars, and
where were they

00:30:50.160 --> 00:30:52.057
going to invest
them, and so forth.

00:30:52.057 --> 00:30:54.390
They managed to manage to
figure out ways to waste them,

00:30:54.390 --> 00:30:55.480
so that was all solved.

00:30:55.480 --> 00:30:59.070
But yeah, that's--

00:31:01.830 --> 00:31:05.460
And the cost now, who knows what
the cost of production is now?

00:31:05.460 --> 00:31:08.730
There's also a number that
you see floating around.

00:31:08.730 --> 00:31:11.450
It's called the "finding cost."

00:31:11.450 --> 00:31:13.950
There's one thing is the cost
of drilling and getting it out

00:31:13.950 --> 00:31:14.533
of the ground.

00:31:14.533 --> 00:31:16.530
The other is the
cost of finding it,

00:31:16.530 --> 00:31:19.060
which is the exploration,
and proving, and so forth.

00:31:19.060 --> 00:31:22.200
And those costs
have gone up a bit.

00:31:22.200 --> 00:31:25.110
The cost of producing it out
of an big known Saudi reserve

00:31:25.110 --> 00:31:28.518
is turning a valve,
almost, short run.

00:31:28.518 --> 00:31:30.060
Long run, you've
got to-- medium run,

00:31:30.060 --> 00:31:32.160
you've got to put the
piping and stuff in.

00:31:32.160 --> 00:31:33.630
Long run, you've got to find it.

00:31:33.630 --> 00:31:37.170
Medium run, cost pretty
low, well below price--

00:31:37.170 --> 00:31:40.810
not off Louisiana.

00:31:40.810 --> 00:31:42.460
That's not far below the price.

00:31:42.460 --> 00:31:43.730
That's expensive stuff.

00:31:43.730 --> 00:31:46.150
So you have a range of costs.

00:31:46.150 --> 00:31:49.940
You have a range of
behaviors in this market.

00:31:49.940 --> 00:31:52.290
Anything else on oil,
questions on oil?

00:31:52.290 --> 00:31:52.790
Yeah.

00:31:52.790 --> 00:31:54.248
AUDIENCE: Did the
sanctions on Iran

00:31:54.248 --> 00:31:56.030
have an effect on the
supply and demand.

00:31:56.030 --> 00:31:57.020
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: What
would have an effect?

00:31:57.020 --> 00:31:59.478
AUDIENCE: The sanctions on Iran
because when Iran sells it,

00:31:59.478 --> 00:32:01.480
it can, pretty much,
with a phone call,

00:32:01.480 --> 00:32:02.730
go anywhere else in the world.

00:32:02.730 --> 00:32:03.680
Really, is it--

00:32:03.680 --> 00:32:05.555
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: I
don't know the answer.

00:32:05.555 --> 00:32:12.380
I know the problem is, if
we don't buy oil from Iran,

00:32:12.380 --> 00:32:13.160
who cares?

00:32:13.160 --> 00:32:15.470
Because they can sell to
other people and they'll

00:32:15.470 --> 00:32:17.550
just displace other suppliers.

00:32:17.550 --> 00:32:21.350
So this was like when the
Arabs refused to sell oil

00:32:21.350 --> 00:32:22.902
to the US in the '70s.

00:32:22.902 --> 00:32:24.110
We had been buying from them.

00:32:24.110 --> 00:32:25.580
We bought from others.

00:32:25.580 --> 00:32:28.680
And their oil went to
others, and so forth.

00:32:28.680 --> 00:32:34.730
If the US, and the EU,
and Japan, let's say,

00:32:34.730 --> 00:32:40.550
have effective refusals
to buy Iranian oil, that's

00:32:40.550 --> 00:32:44.365
enough that it might be hard for
them to find demand elsewhere.

00:32:48.140 --> 00:32:51.270
It gets to be a
quantitative question.

00:32:51.270 --> 00:32:56.130
If we can block
enough exits for them,

00:32:56.130 --> 00:32:58.730
they may have a hard
time selling it.

00:32:58.730 --> 00:33:01.630
The question is, who buys then?

00:33:01.630 --> 00:33:04.060
So I just don't know
whether it's had an effect

00:33:04.060 --> 00:33:07.210
or whether people really think
it's going to have an effect.

00:33:07.210 --> 00:33:08.440
There are a lot of people--

00:33:08.440 --> 00:33:09.940
I mean, a lot of
the other sanctions

00:33:09.940 --> 00:33:11.320
have had an effect on Iran.

00:33:11.320 --> 00:33:13.570
You read discussions about
living in Iran these days.

00:33:13.570 --> 00:33:15.640
It's not very good.

00:33:15.640 --> 00:33:17.500
The economy is pretty
much in the toilet,

00:33:17.500 --> 00:33:20.020
but how much of that's
the oil sanctions

00:33:20.020 --> 00:33:23.630
and how much is everything else
we've done, I just don't know.

00:33:23.630 --> 00:33:24.130
OK.

00:33:24.130 --> 00:33:24.910
Anything else?

00:33:24.910 --> 00:33:25.890
Yeah, Scott.

00:33:25.890 --> 00:33:27.470
AUDIENCE: Can we go back to
the slide with the picture

00:33:27.470 --> 00:33:29.500
where the oil from different
countries are going?

00:33:29.500 --> 00:33:30.875
I had a question
about something.

00:33:30.875 --> 00:33:38.500
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Yeah-- not quickly.

00:33:38.500 --> 00:33:39.120
There.

00:33:39.120 --> 00:33:39.953
AUDIENCE: All right.

00:33:39.953 --> 00:33:43.810
So it looks like the oil from
the US is going into Mexico,

00:33:43.810 --> 00:33:46.030
and then the oil from
Mexico is going into the US.

00:33:46.030 --> 00:33:47.340
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Yeah,
there's a little border trade.

00:33:47.340 --> 00:33:48.610
It's not a big number.

00:33:48.610 --> 00:33:51.310
AUDIENCE: So is that
because it's cheaper

00:33:51.310 --> 00:33:54.377
to buy oil from Mexico than
to produce it ourselves?

00:33:54.377 --> 00:33:56.710
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Well,
some of it is just geography.

00:33:56.710 --> 00:33:59.620
I mean, I'm little
surprised by that.

00:33:59.620 --> 00:34:01.000
You always see it
in the numbers,

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:03.070
that we're exporting
something to somebody.

00:34:03.070 --> 00:34:07.900
It must be-- and some of this
is refined product rather than

00:34:07.900 --> 00:34:08.590
crude.

00:34:08.590 --> 00:34:10.989
So yeah, maybe we
have a refinery here

00:34:10.989 --> 00:34:15.820
that it makes sense to export
refined product to Monterrey.

00:34:15.820 --> 00:34:16.900
And they happen to have--

00:34:16.900 --> 00:34:17.500
I don't know where they're--

00:34:17.500 --> 00:34:18.880
I don't think they have
any fields up here.

00:34:18.880 --> 00:34:20.650
I'm not sure what
they're exporting to us,

00:34:20.650 --> 00:34:25.449
but I'm assuming that some
of this is refined product.

00:34:25.449 --> 00:34:27.219
I don't know why would
be shipping crude.

00:34:27.219 --> 00:34:30.850
And I talk about
this as if it's easy,

00:34:30.850 --> 00:34:34.449
but this is pipeline,
the US-Mexico's pipeline.

00:34:34.449 --> 00:34:37.659
It's almost
certainly not tanker.

00:34:37.659 --> 00:34:39.580
And of course, it's
where are the pipelines,

00:34:39.580 --> 00:34:41.020
where are the demands.

00:34:41.020 --> 00:34:44.020
You could imagine as
Monterrey grows in Mexico,

00:34:44.020 --> 00:34:46.060
it might be cheaper
since it's in the north.

00:34:46.060 --> 00:34:49.210
It might be cheaper to supply
it from the southern US

00:34:49.210 --> 00:34:51.699
than from farther
south in Mexico.

00:34:51.699 --> 00:34:53.050
And maybe this is tanker.

00:34:53.050 --> 00:34:55.870
Maybe they put stuff and
take it to the West Coast.

00:34:55.870 --> 00:34:57.910
I don't know, but
you've got to figure

00:34:57.910 --> 00:35:02.440
this has as much to do with
transport costs, pipeline

00:35:02.440 --> 00:35:05.230
location, shipping
cost, refineries,

00:35:05.230 --> 00:35:09.050
as getting it out of the ground.

00:35:09.050 --> 00:35:10.880
Mexico has a little
bit of a problem.

00:35:10.880 --> 00:35:15.050
Mexico has a constitutional
bar against foreigners

00:35:15.050 --> 00:35:17.130
owning natural resources.

00:35:17.130 --> 00:35:21.170
And that means they've operated
with a state-owned oil company

00:35:21.170 --> 00:35:23.960
since the 1911--

00:35:23.960 --> 00:35:26.780
no, since the 1930s
when they kicked out

00:35:26.780 --> 00:35:28.490
the foreigners completely.

00:35:28.490 --> 00:35:31.010
And the state-owned oil
company has been inefficient

00:35:31.010 --> 00:35:33.470
and has had a hard time
getting technology.

00:35:33.470 --> 00:35:37.250
So they're facing
production declines,

00:35:37.250 --> 00:35:39.500
and facing
constitutional problems

00:35:39.500 --> 00:35:41.810
of how do you bring
in foreign technology.

00:35:41.810 --> 00:35:44.720
So it's sort of an
interesting question.

00:35:44.720 --> 00:35:45.520
Yeah.

00:35:45.520 --> 00:35:48.600
AUDIENCE: Oh, sorry, just
to throw some light on that.

00:35:48.600 --> 00:35:50.760
When I worked at JPM
on the crude oil desk,

00:35:50.760 --> 00:35:52.760
one of the things they
used to always talk about

00:35:52.760 --> 00:35:55.460
was the geographic difference
between a defense district

00:35:55.460 --> 00:35:59.990
called PAD 5 over there, which
includes all of the West Coast.

00:35:59.990 --> 00:36:02.330
And there's severe
geographical limitations

00:36:02.330 --> 00:36:04.620
that don't allow oil to
actually be transported.

00:36:04.620 --> 00:36:06.980
So they actually trade
completely differently

00:36:06.980 --> 00:36:08.420
in terms of oil pricing.

00:36:08.420 --> 00:36:11.120
And because a lot of our oil
comes from Cushing, Oklahoma,

00:36:11.120 --> 00:36:13.850
which is like that
central point over there,

00:36:13.850 --> 00:36:17.120
they might have to exchange
it across international lines,

00:36:17.120 --> 00:36:18.650
even if it's crude oil.

00:36:18.650 --> 00:36:21.150
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: You think
it might be refined in Mexico

00:36:21.150 --> 00:36:22.778
and brought back as product.

00:36:22.778 --> 00:36:23.278
Yeah.

00:36:23.278 --> 00:36:26.210
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:36:26.210 --> 00:36:29.734
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Yeah, that's a nice point.

00:36:29.734 --> 00:36:32.992
They're called PADs, or
Petroleum Allocation Districts,

00:36:32.992 --> 00:36:33.950
or something like that.

00:36:33.950 --> 00:36:35.200
It's a Cold War term, I think.

00:36:35.200 --> 00:36:37.325
AUDIENCE: Defense district
also included somewhere.

00:36:37.325 --> 00:36:38.660
It was created during wartime.

00:36:38.660 --> 00:36:40.077
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Yeah, I think

00:36:40.077 --> 00:36:41.430
that's a World War II thing.

00:36:41.430 --> 00:36:43.580
It's not real easy
to pump anything

00:36:43.580 --> 00:36:45.470
across the Rocky Mountains.

00:36:45.470 --> 00:36:50.120
And so the West Coast tends
to operate separately.

00:36:50.120 --> 00:36:53.180
Alaskan oil tends
to come down here,

00:36:53.180 --> 00:36:56.360
even though it'd be better
to sell it to Japan.

00:36:56.360 --> 00:36:59.030
And of course, Canadian oil--

00:36:59.030 --> 00:37:00.710
you know the Keystone
Pipeline debate,

00:37:00.710 --> 00:37:01.877
if you've been following it.

00:37:01.877 --> 00:37:04.310
Where Canadian oil goes is
another interesting question.

00:37:04.310 --> 00:37:06.530
But yeah, that's interesting.

00:37:06.530 --> 00:37:11.060
It may be that it's cheaper to
get Mexican oil into California

00:37:11.060 --> 00:37:13.940
than to get oil from
elsewhere in the US,

00:37:13.940 --> 00:37:15.710
and that some US oil--

00:37:15.710 --> 00:37:18.470
this is the puzzler,
that we're shipping.

00:37:18.470 --> 00:37:20.930
It may be to be
refined in Mexico.

00:37:20.930 --> 00:37:23.787
It may be refined product
into the north of Mexico

00:37:23.787 --> 00:37:25.370
if they're short of
refinery capacity.

00:37:25.370 --> 00:37:26.810
AUDIENCE: I think the
oil pipelines go straight

00:37:26.810 --> 00:37:27.352
into Cushing.

00:37:27.352 --> 00:37:28.435
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Yeah.

00:37:28.435 --> 00:37:30.650
AUDIENCE: They might not
be able to even reverse

00:37:30.650 --> 00:37:33.140
the flow, which they've
actually been doing recently.

00:37:33.140 --> 00:37:35.107
But back then, maybe,
when this was made,

00:37:35.107 --> 00:37:36.440
they weren't able to reverse it.

00:37:36.440 --> 00:37:38.843
So they have to move it and
then actually physically

00:37:38.843 --> 00:37:39.510
bring it around.

00:37:39.510 --> 00:37:42.260
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Well, these are 2010.

00:37:42.260 --> 00:37:43.410
these are 2010 data.

00:37:43.410 --> 00:37:43.910
So--

00:37:43.910 --> 00:37:46.250
AUDIENCE: I think the reversal
happened just this year.

00:37:46.250 --> 00:37:48.610
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: This year.

00:37:48.610 --> 00:37:51.130
OK, happy to learn.

00:37:51.130 --> 00:37:53.300
Anything else?

00:37:53.300 --> 00:37:55.160
OK, let me go to coal.

00:37:58.500 --> 00:38:01.130
Coal is concentrated.

00:38:01.130 --> 00:38:05.970
As that earlier case indicated,
we're probably the OPEC of coal

00:38:05.970 --> 00:38:07.890
or the Saudi Arabia of coal.

00:38:07.890 --> 00:38:09.528
It is traded.

00:38:09.528 --> 00:38:11.070
Coal trades
internationally, and I'll

00:38:11.070 --> 00:38:12.850
show you some numbers on that.

00:38:12.850 --> 00:38:16.540
But it has a high
weight to value ratio.

00:38:16.540 --> 00:38:18.930
So it's not quite as
easy to handle as oil

00:38:18.930 --> 00:38:21.450
and it's not quite
as valuable as oil.

00:38:21.450 --> 00:38:24.030
So it's like international
trade in rocks.

00:38:24.030 --> 00:38:26.730
There is some, but
there isn't that much

00:38:26.730 --> 00:38:28.740
because it's expensive.

00:38:28.740 --> 00:38:30.520
Markets are mainly national.

00:38:30.520 --> 00:38:31.890
There are some differences.

00:38:31.890 --> 00:38:36.420
We tend to have lower
prices than elsewhere.

00:38:36.420 --> 00:38:39.870
This isn't a business where
there are a lot of spot markets

00:38:39.870 --> 00:38:40.830
and futures markets.

00:38:40.830 --> 00:38:44.460
There are some, but it's
mostly long-term contracts.

00:38:44.460 --> 00:38:49.200
And the world fact is this
unbelievable recent increase

00:38:49.200 --> 00:38:51.810
in the Chinese use of coal
that we talked about earlier--

00:38:51.810 --> 00:38:54.360
"unbelievable" is the
wrong term, but it's huge.

00:38:54.360 --> 00:38:57.870
I have to say I revised this
from last year's lecture.

00:38:57.870 --> 00:39:00.540
And the Chinese numbers
are dramatically different.

00:39:00.540 --> 00:39:02.770
It's kind of shocking.

00:39:02.770 --> 00:39:05.400
This is production and reserves.

00:39:05.400 --> 00:39:08.730
So you will see we have over
a quarter of the world's coal

00:39:08.730 --> 00:39:09.840
reserves.

00:39:09.840 --> 00:39:12.480
China sort of comes in--

00:39:12.480 --> 00:39:15.150
well, Russia comes
in second at 18%.

00:39:15.150 --> 00:39:19.380
China comes in third, but look
at that-- the Chinese produce

00:39:19.380 --> 00:39:26.448
almost half the coal in
the world, 48% as of 2010.

00:39:26.448 --> 00:39:28.240
That's a number that
deserves to be in red.

00:39:28.240 --> 00:39:31.630
It was somewhere in the 20s
the last time I did this.

00:39:31.630 --> 00:39:35.050
Well, I did it two years ago,
so somewhere in the 20s or 30s.

00:39:35.050 --> 00:39:38.740
But it's relatively
concentrated.

00:39:38.740 --> 00:39:41.380
These five countries
account for 80% of output

00:39:41.380 --> 00:39:44.000
and three-quarters of reserves.

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:45.558
Again, these are
reserves, of course.

00:39:45.558 --> 00:39:48.100
Does that mean we've looked for
coal everywhere in the world?

00:39:48.100 --> 00:39:49.373
No.

00:39:49.373 --> 00:39:51.040
Does that mean there
isn't a lot of coal

00:39:51.040 --> 00:39:52.207
in places we haven't looked?

00:39:52.207 --> 00:39:52.810
No.

00:39:52.810 --> 00:39:54.185
But we've looked
in these places,

00:39:54.185 --> 00:39:56.980
and we found a lot of it
in the US and a lot of it

00:39:56.980 --> 00:39:58.090
in China and Russia.

00:39:58.090 --> 00:39:59.770
There may be some--

00:39:59.770 --> 00:40:01.210
people talk about
coal in Africa,

00:40:01.210 --> 00:40:05.670
but there hasn't been
that much exploration.

00:40:05.670 --> 00:40:08.580
Only about 15% of
production of coal

00:40:08.580 --> 00:40:09.930
crosses international lines.

00:40:09.930 --> 00:40:12.840
So it really isn't like oil.

00:40:12.840 --> 00:40:15.630
These are the big exporters.

00:40:15.630 --> 00:40:18.300
And I didn't add up the
shares, but you can do that.

00:40:18.300 --> 00:40:23.970
We do export out of both coasts,
but I think mostly the East

00:40:23.970 --> 00:40:25.230
Coast to Europe.

00:40:25.230 --> 00:40:29.660
The big exporters, though,
are Australia and Indonesia.

00:40:29.660 --> 00:40:31.970
And if you look at who
the big importers are,

00:40:31.970 --> 00:40:35.000
you can see immediately
where it goes.

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:36.800
Not only does China
produce a lot of coal,

00:40:36.800 --> 00:40:39.860
but they're the second-leading
importer of coal.

00:40:39.860 --> 00:40:42.200
So you have Australian
and Indonesian coal

00:40:42.200 --> 00:40:45.900
going, to a decent
approximation, China, Japan,

00:40:45.900 --> 00:40:47.780
and South Korea--

00:40:47.780 --> 00:40:50.960
again, fairly concentrated.

00:40:50.960 --> 00:40:56.030
Expensive, not cheap to ship
this stuff, but huge demands.

00:40:56.030 --> 00:40:57.350
Japan has no energy.

00:40:57.350 --> 00:40:59.750
China has coal, but
China needs more coal

00:40:59.750 --> 00:41:02.330
than it can produce
in the short run.

00:41:02.330 --> 00:41:03.660
So that's the flow.

00:41:03.660 --> 00:41:05.120
I don't have a good picture.

00:41:05.120 --> 00:41:06.260
Not a world market.

00:41:06.260 --> 00:41:09.350
You can't read this
well, but these are

00:41:09.350 --> 00:41:11.930
Japanese prices in this column.

00:41:11.930 --> 00:41:13.835
Those are the ones that matter.

00:41:19.630 --> 00:41:21.340
Either column, you
will see they're

00:41:21.340 --> 00:41:24.220
higher than the US
prices typically.

00:41:24.220 --> 00:41:28.120
And the European prices are a
bit higher than the US prices

00:41:28.120 --> 00:41:29.290
typically.

00:41:29.290 --> 00:41:31.830
You can't do that for oil.

00:41:31.830 --> 00:41:35.140
The price of oil
is pretty uniform.

00:41:35.140 --> 00:41:38.500
But you can for coal.

00:41:38.500 --> 00:41:41.510
And this is the graph
that's shocking.

00:41:41.510 --> 00:41:43.240
This is world coal use.

00:41:43.240 --> 00:41:46.540
You see it rising gently
and then exploding.

00:41:46.540 --> 00:41:48.790
And if you look
behind that picture,

00:41:48.790 --> 00:41:51.610
the explosion is mostly China.

00:41:58.060 --> 00:42:02.560
In the US, it's worth
looking at states.

00:42:02.560 --> 00:42:06.430
Production is
fairly concentrated.

00:42:06.430 --> 00:42:13.180
Wyoming coal is mined mostly
big strip-mining operations,

00:42:13.180 --> 00:42:17.950
massive strip-mining operations,
close to the surface.

00:42:17.950 --> 00:42:19.240
Surface is taken off.

00:42:19.240 --> 00:42:19.810
You go down.

00:42:19.810 --> 00:42:22.610
You strip away a layer of coal.

00:42:22.610 --> 00:42:24.520
This coal tends to
have a low sulfur

00:42:24.520 --> 00:42:27.610
content, the Western
coal, the Wyoming coal.

00:42:27.610 --> 00:42:31.930
So it's less polluting
on that dimension.

00:42:31.930 --> 00:42:34.270
There is a mix of low-
and high-sulfur coal

00:42:34.270 --> 00:42:38.480
in these main mining regions
in the East, West Virginia,

00:42:38.480 --> 00:42:41.800
Kentucky, and Pennsylvania.

00:42:41.800 --> 00:42:45.040
So those five states account
for almost three-quarters

00:42:45.040 --> 00:42:47.110
of production.

00:42:47.110 --> 00:42:49.750
Consumption is much
less concentrated.

00:42:49.750 --> 00:42:51.250
This is for power
plants, but that's

00:42:51.250 --> 00:42:53.260
almost all coal consumption--

00:42:53.260 --> 00:42:55.840
Texas, Ohio-- these
are the states

00:42:55.840 --> 00:42:58.480
with cheap electric
rates because they

00:42:58.480 --> 00:43:00.310
burn a lot of coal.

00:43:03.420 --> 00:43:06.710
I got anything else on coal?

00:43:06.710 --> 00:43:08.660
Yeah, that's about it on coal.

00:43:08.660 --> 00:43:11.960
Questions, comments,
reactions about coal?

00:43:11.960 --> 00:43:13.700
Not the most
exciting of products,

00:43:13.700 --> 00:43:18.350
but very important and dirty--

00:43:18.350 --> 00:43:21.520
not to be prejudicial.

00:43:21.520 --> 00:43:22.840
Anything?

00:43:22.840 --> 00:43:26.290
OK, I'll say a little
bit about uranium.

00:43:26.290 --> 00:43:30.160
There isn't much that you
can find about uranium--

00:43:30.160 --> 00:43:33.400
essentially nothing
in the BP book.

00:43:33.400 --> 00:43:35.980
And I'm focusing on uranium
rather than nuclear power

00:43:35.980 --> 00:43:40.000
because that's the
nonrenewable part, is uranium.

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:42.845
But it's also
relatively unimportant.

00:43:42.845 --> 00:43:44.470
I mean, it's not an
important component

00:43:44.470 --> 00:43:49.390
of the cost of
nuclear electricity.

00:43:49.390 --> 00:43:51.070
It does seem to be
a global market.

00:43:51.070 --> 00:43:53.440
I'll explain that
in a little bit.

00:43:53.440 --> 00:43:56.470
Reserves are fairly dispersed.

00:43:56.470 --> 00:44:00.550
I mean, again, not clear there's
been extensive exploration

00:44:00.550 --> 00:44:02.200
in lots of these places.

00:44:02.200 --> 00:44:05.620
You remember the
yellowcake from Niger,

00:44:05.620 --> 00:44:08.020
very exciting in the run-up
to the second Gulf War.

00:44:14.110 --> 00:44:15.880
I had a price graph.

00:44:15.880 --> 00:44:17.080
It's not very interesting.

00:44:17.080 --> 00:44:18.820
It's mostly long-term prices.

00:44:18.820 --> 00:44:21.310
They're are just flat
from the mid '80s

00:44:21.310 --> 00:44:24.070
through the mid '90s,
or the early '80s

00:44:24.070 --> 00:44:25.060
through the mid '90s.

00:44:25.060 --> 00:44:26.830
And then they began to escalate.

00:44:26.830 --> 00:44:29.110
And basically in
that early period,

00:44:29.110 --> 00:44:31.390
people just stopped
producing uranium.

00:44:31.390 --> 00:44:32.740
And now they've tripled.

00:44:32.740 --> 00:44:34.840
There's new mining activity.

00:44:34.840 --> 00:44:37.240
There's really no
organized market

00:44:37.240 --> 00:44:41.380
as there is for oil, or even
to some extent for coal.

00:44:41.380 --> 00:44:43.510
These are long-term contracts.

00:44:43.510 --> 00:44:44.620
There's a spot market.

00:44:44.620 --> 00:44:45.910
It's not very interesting.

00:44:45.910 --> 00:44:46.555
It's very thin.

00:44:49.280 --> 00:44:54.490
We import almost all of the
uranium we use in US reactors--

00:44:54.490 --> 00:44:58.630
92%, a lot of it from
Australia and Canada,

00:44:58.630 --> 00:45:02.530
and then from Russia and
a couple of the 'Stans.

00:45:02.530 --> 00:45:06.880
And production is more
concentrated than reserves,

00:45:06.880 --> 00:45:11.020
so those countries
have 93% of production.

00:45:11.020 --> 00:45:14.050
Kazakhstan is a big producer,
Canada, Australia, and then

00:45:14.050 --> 00:45:15.700
it falls off relatively rapidly.

00:45:15.700 --> 00:45:19.360
We account for about 3%
of global production.

00:45:19.360 --> 00:45:26.340
So not a terribly exciting,
not a terribly big market.

00:45:26.340 --> 00:45:29.530
Anything about uranium?

00:45:29.530 --> 00:45:31.830
This is fairly boring
stuff, but you sort of

00:45:31.830 --> 00:45:34.830
do need to have some basic
factual understanding of what

00:45:34.830 --> 00:45:38.640
these markets look
like if you're going

00:45:38.640 --> 00:45:40.680
to be in the energy business.

00:45:40.680 --> 00:45:41.670
Let me do gas.

00:45:41.670 --> 00:45:43.241
Gas is more interesting.

00:45:46.272 --> 00:45:47.730
You may at some
point have wondered

00:45:47.730 --> 00:45:49.140
why we call it "natural gas."

00:45:49.140 --> 00:45:53.490
It's not all that obvious, but
it's because beginning in 1816

00:45:53.490 --> 00:45:54.875
we produced gas from coal.

00:45:54.875 --> 00:45:56.250
I don't know how
early in Europe,

00:45:56.250 --> 00:45:59.160
but in this country in 1816.

00:45:59.160 --> 00:46:00.030
You heat coal.

00:46:00.030 --> 00:46:00.810
It gives off gas.

00:46:00.810 --> 00:46:01.920
You put the gas in a pipe.

00:46:01.920 --> 00:46:05.400
You ship it around the city
and use it for lighting.

00:46:05.400 --> 00:46:07.350
That was gas.

00:46:07.350 --> 00:46:10.233
Natural gas was the
innovation-- that you

00:46:10.233 --> 00:46:11.400
didn't produce it from coal.

00:46:11.400 --> 00:46:16.660
You got it naturally,
hence "natural gas."

00:46:16.660 --> 00:46:19.770
It can be moved by pipeline.

00:46:19.770 --> 00:46:23.400
To move it by ship, you
have to liquefy it, cool it,

00:46:23.400 --> 00:46:24.910
and compress it.

00:46:24.910 --> 00:46:28.270
It is not a global market.

00:46:28.270 --> 00:46:33.000
As we'll talk about next
time, that might change--

00:46:33.000 --> 00:46:35.040
lots of interesting
discussions there.

00:46:35.040 --> 00:46:35.820
That might change.

00:46:41.181 --> 00:46:42.957
This is circa 2010.

00:46:42.957 --> 00:46:43.665
This will change.

00:46:46.530 --> 00:46:49.650
We produce about 85%
of the gas we consume.

00:46:49.650 --> 00:46:53.280
Most of the rest is from
Canada, so North America

00:46:53.280 --> 00:46:57.000
is pretty much
self-sufficient in gas.

00:46:57.000 --> 00:47:00.820
Most of our imports--

00:47:00.820 --> 00:47:02.610
no, it's not on this slide.

00:47:02.610 --> 00:47:06.330
The way the prices
work, US prices

00:47:06.330 --> 00:47:08.640
tend to be below
European prices.

00:47:08.640 --> 00:47:13.530
European prices are determined
by Russian gas prices,

00:47:13.530 --> 00:47:15.240
and they're much lower
than Asian prices,

00:47:15.240 --> 00:47:20.710
because Asia's gas tends to
come via liquefied natural gas,

00:47:20.710 --> 00:47:24.310
which is expensive.

00:47:24.310 --> 00:47:28.360
Historically, if I were
doing this-- well, when

00:47:28.360 --> 00:47:31.720
I did this class two years
ago, this sort of stopped here.

00:47:31.720 --> 00:47:34.120
Gas reserves are
associated with oil.

00:47:34.120 --> 00:47:36.730
They tend to be in
politically unstable places.

00:47:36.730 --> 00:47:40.190
The gas we know most about is in
unstable regions in the Middle

00:47:40.190 --> 00:47:43.660
East and, if you think
it's unstable, Russia.

00:47:43.660 --> 00:47:45.940
But that has
changed dramatically

00:47:45.940 --> 00:47:48.460
in literally the last
three or four years.

00:47:51.380 --> 00:47:56.610
Shale gas can be produced
cheaply, not necessarily

00:47:56.610 --> 00:48:00.720
without environmental
costs, but cheaply.

00:48:00.720 --> 00:48:04.706
And once again, the US is
lucky-- we have a lot of it.

00:48:04.706 --> 00:48:07.460
We now have the ability
to produce a lot of gas

00:48:07.460 --> 00:48:12.980
cheaply with environmental
costs, potentially.

00:48:12.980 --> 00:48:16.930
We think China has
that same ability.

00:48:16.930 --> 00:48:18.370
Some European countries do.

00:48:18.370 --> 00:48:20.300
We're told it's under Paris.

00:48:20.300 --> 00:48:23.860
Paris is resisting drilling--

00:48:23.860 --> 00:48:26.440
makes a good story,
even if it's not true.

00:48:26.440 --> 00:48:28.930
Might be true.

00:48:28.930 --> 00:48:34.030
I want to focus on this change
on Wednesday, because as I say,

00:48:34.030 --> 00:48:36.820
this is the biggest
energy change, certainly

00:48:36.820 --> 00:48:37.888
in my lifetime.

00:48:37.888 --> 00:48:39.430
Well, maybe OPEC
was bigger, but it's

00:48:39.430 --> 00:48:45.130
close to OPEC in terms of a
change in the energy landscape.

00:48:45.130 --> 00:48:52.130
But what we do about it is
subject to serious debate.

00:48:52.130 --> 00:48:54.130
And I want to try to
outline that and get

00:48:54.130 --> 00:48:56.110
you to engage a little bit.

00:48:56.110 --> 00:48:58.060
There are those who
say we should not

00:48:58.060 --> 00:49:01.190
be using this technology.

00:49:01.190 --> 00:49:04.840
New York State
does not allow it.

00:49:04.840 --> 00:49:08.080
North Dakota
eagerly embraces it,

00:49:08.080 --> 00:49:11.470
is thrilled to have
jobs, actually, in North

00:49:11.470 --> 00:49:15.290
Dakota, and boomtowns, and cheap
liquor, and everything else--

00:49:15.290 --> 00:49:17.680
all the other good things
that come with a boomtown.

00:49:21.790 --> 00:49:26.770
But as a country,
we have some issues.

00:49:26.770 --> 00:49:31.030
There's a question of its
impact on climate change.

00:49:31.030 --> 00:49:33.850
You sort of think cheap
gas would be good,

00:49:33.850 --> 00:49:35.530
but what if it leaks?

00:49:35.530 --> 00:49:39.460
So I want to spend
next time on that.

00:49:39.460 --> 00:49:42.250
Today, I want to just
go through some sort

00:49:42.250 --> 00:49:48.490
of pre-fracking facts, if
I can say that, and lay

00:49:48.490 --> 00:49:50.380
the groundwork.

00:49:50.380 --> 00:49:52.240
So this is gas trade.

00:49:52.240 --> 00:49:57.230
Most of it-- well, 70% of
it-- moves via pipelines.

00:49:57.230 --> 00:50:00.770
And again, if you focus
on the big numbers,

00:50:00.770 --> 00:50:04.850
you see Russian gas
moving into Europe.

00:50:04.850 --> 00:50:07.970
And you see gas from the
Middle East, importantly,

00:50:07.970 --> 00:50:09.050
moving to Asia.

00:50:09.050 --> 00:50:11.750
But it's not moving by
pipeline across China.

00:50:11.750 --> 00:50:14.230
It's moving liquefied by tanker.

00:50:14.230 --> 00:50:15.890
There are some exports
from Indonesia,

00:50:15.890 --> 00:50:20.570
some exports from Australia,
and a little gas into the US.

00:50:20.570 --> 00:50:25.580
Big imports from Canada,
relatively speaking,

00:50:25.580 --> 00:50:27.680
and I guess we
export to Mexico--

00:50:27.680 --> 00:50:31.130
again, just because we can.

00:50:31.130 --> 00:50:33.590
That's got to be just geography.

00:50:33.590 --> 00:50:36.530
As I say, most of
it's by pipeline.

00:50:36.530 --> 00:50:41.630
If you look at the output,
Russia is the big producer.

00:50:41.630 --> 00:50:44.720
Russia produces 15% of the
natural gas in the world.

00:50:44.720 --> 00:50:46.400
The Middle East together--

00:50:46.400 --> 00:50:49.400
and it's really hard to see
it on this lousy picture--

00:50:49.400 --> 00:50:51.800
produces 14%.

00:50:51.800 --> 00:50:57.020
Reserves-- once again,
Russia is producing

00:50:57.020 --> 00:50:59.480
a lot out of its 24%
of the world reserves.

00:50:59.480 --> 00:51:04.520
The Middle East has 40%
proved reserves as of 2010.

00:51:04.520 --> 00:51:05.990
The US had 5%.

00:51:05.990 --> 00:51:11.030
This picture will change because
you see now, with shale gas,

00:51:11.030 --> 00:51:16.220
estimates of recoverable gas--
not yet a proven reserve--

00:51:16.220 --> 00:51:18.130
are anomalous.

00:51:18.130 --> 00:51:23.200
So as exploration adds
to this inventory,

00:51:23.200 --> 00:51:25.460
the US number will rise.

00:51:25.460 --> 00:51:28.630
I don't know if the Middle East
has shale or Russia has shale.

00:51:28.630 --> 00:51:31.690
China will show
up on the picture.

00:51:31.690 --> 00:51:34.510
And if they allow drilling
in Poland, Poland, I'm told,

00:51:34.510 --> 00:51:35.680
has a fair amount.

00:51:35.680 --> 00:51:37.670
So that picture will change.

00:51:37.670 --> 00:51:40.510
This is just with
a proved reserve.

00:51:40.510 --> 00:51:42.300
But again, it's the
same picture as oil.

00:51:45.840 --> 00:51:48.390
The one exception-- and I
guess this is a little bit

00:51:48.390 --> 00:51:50.070
interesting--

00:51:50.070 --> 00:51:54.450
you'll see the share of the
Middle East actually rises.

00:51:54.450 --> 00:51:57.310
Not only does it rise in
absolute value, of course,

00:51:57.310 --> 00:51:59.777
it rises in share.

00:51:59.777 --> 00:52:01.860
And you will recall when
we did the climate change

00:52:01.860 --> 00:52:05.580
negotiations, you were
in Qatar or "cutter"

00:52:05.580 --> 00:52:07.200
as it's sometimes called.

00:52:07.200 --> 00:52:12.840
That's their discovery of their
enormous natural gas reserves.

00:52:12.840 --> 00:52:15.450
That's one formerly
poor, little country

00:52:15.450 --> 00:52:20.610
finding it is sitting on an
enormous amount of natural gas,

00:52:20.610 --> 00:52:23.785
and that's the Middle
Eastern change primarily.

00:52:23.785 --> 00:52:25.410
Other people are
developing, of course,

00:52:25.410 --> 00:52:27.310
but that's what's
going on there.

00:52:27.310 --> 00:52:32.580
And as I say, that North
America, which I guess

00:52:32.580 --> 00:52:36.150
is this one--

00:52:36.150 --> 00:52:40.340
that will change over time
because we have a lot of gas.

00:52:40.340 --> 00:52:43.640
But it's not yet proven,
not yet proved reserves.

00:52:43.640 --> 00:52:46.820
It's oh, my god, look at what's
almost certainly down there,

00:52:46.820 --> 00:52:47.530
but it's not--

00:52:50.110 --> 00:52:52.420
We have a lot of pipelines.

00:52:52.420 --> 00:52:54.110
This is how you
move natural gas.

00:52:54.110 --> 00:52:57.770
This is just a map of
the US pipeline network.

00:52:57.770 --> 00:53:05.620
And here we are at the end
of the straw, as they say.

00:53:05.620 --> 00:53:08.260
So every so often,
there isn't enough gas

00:53:08.260 --> 00:53:09.820
coming up to
Massachusetts-- most

00:53:09.820 --> 00:53:12.220
of the time, not a problem.

00:53:12.220 --> 00:53:15.470
You hear about the Henry Hub.

00:53:15.470 --> 00:53:17.240
Well, if you follow
this business,

00:53:17.240 --> 00:53:19.550
you hear about Henry Hub.

00:53:19.550 --> 00:53:23.150
Henry Hub is about there.

00:53:23.150 --> 00:53:24.860
There's a lot of
offshore pipelines,

00:53:24.860 --> 00:53:27.740
but Henry Hub is in
southern Louisiana

00:53:27.740 --> 00:53:30.650
a little bit east of the center.

00:53:30.650 --> 00:53:34.490
And it's where something
like 13 pipelines come in--

00:53:34.490 --> 00:53:38.240
nine interstate and
four intrastate.

00:53:38.240 --> 00:53:41.030
And when you hear
the Henry Hub price,

00:53:41.030 --> 00:53:45.860
pricing of natural gas
in wholesale markets

00:53:45.860 --> 00:53:50.640
is mostly the price at the
Henry Hub plus transport cost.

00:53:50.640 --> 00:53:53.580
So people do futures
markets based on Henry Hub,

00:53:53.580 --> 00:53:55.080
and then you add
in transport costs.

00:53:55.080 --> 00:53:58.710
You do a contract on a Henry
Hub price and a transport.

00:53:58.710 --> 00:54:01.410
So when I say gas moves
mainly by pipelines,

00:54:01.410 --> 00:54:03.660
it moves in the US
a lot by pipelines.

00:54:03.660 --> 00:54:08.760
You can also tell by the
pipelines where it comes from.

00:54:08.760 --> 00:54:12.510
At the moment, it comes
from Louisiana, Texas.

00:54:12.510 --> 00:54:14.100
It comes from offshore.

00:54:14.100 --> 00:54:15.540
That's northern Louisiana.

00:54:15.540 --> 00:54:16.770
That's Oklahoma.

00:54:16.770 --> 00:54:19.570
And that's mainly it.

00:54:19.570 --> 00:54:21.650
That will change.

00:54:21.650 --> 00:54:25.160
It's coming from North
Dakota, where you

00:54:25.160 --> 00:54:27.170
don't see a lot of pipelines.

00:54:27.170 --> 00:54:30.440
It's relatively easy to build
gas pipelines in this country,

00:54:30.440 --> 00:54:36.320
so they will be built.

00:54:36.320 --> 00:54:40.670
Natural gas-- these are prices.

00:54:40.670 --> 00:54:42.650
So this is the US
Henry Hub price

00:54:42.650 --> 00:54:46.490
in red, the UK price,
the Japanese price,

00:54:46.490 --> 00:54:48.020
and the German price.

00:54:48.020 --> 00:54:54.250
You will see in recent years,
at least, there's the US price,

00:54:54.250 --> 00:54:59.330
there's the UK price,
there is the German price,

00:54:59.330 --> 00:55:04.370
which is a Russian price, and
there's the Japanese price.

00:55:04.370 --> 00:55:08.620
So you can sort
of see why there's

00:55:08.620 --> 00:55:15.350
some interest in this country
in exporting natural gas.

00:55:15.350 --> 00:55:17.570
If you can actually
produce it for that price

00:55:17.570 --> 00:55:21.220
and sell it to Japan, you
might eat half the difference

00:55:21.220 --> 00:55:25.340
in transport, but
that's a huge margin.

00:55:25.340 --> 00:55:28.240
So we have built terminals to
import natural gas that are now

00:55:28.240 --> 00:55:30.250
being converted to export.

00:55:32.982 --> 00:55:34.940
Well, they're trying to
convert them to export.

00:55:34.940 --> 00:55:40.595
And here is a historical
price series that cuts off.

00:55:40.595 --> 00:55:42.970
I thought this was a defect
of the way I got the picture,

00:55:42.970 --> 00:55:47.830
but I now see in terms of the
flow here, it's a feature.

00:55:47.830 --> 00:55:50.230
This cuts off about 2009.

00:55:50.230 --> 00:55:54.190
We will explore the
rest on Wednesday.

