Yeah.

00:56:36.920 --> 00:56:39.710
AUDIENCE: So gas tends
to occur with oil

00:56:39.710 --> 00:56:41.690
as in wherever there's
an oil reserve they're

00:56:41.690 --> 00:56:43.085
surrounded by gas or something?

00:56:43.085 --> 00:56:44.210
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Often.

00:56:44.210 --> 00:56:45.590
Not always, but often.

00:56:45.590 --> 00:56:49.320
Because these are fossils.

00:56:49.320 --> 00:56:51.753
These are dead
dinosaurs and trees.

00:56:51.753 --> 00:56:54.170
AUDIENCE: So a lot of companies
are oil and gas companies,

00:56:54.170 --> 00:56:55.850
often, not coal
and gas companies?

00:56:55.850 --> 00:56:56.690
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Yeah, because they

00:56:56.690 --> 00:56:57.900
tend to be co-located.

00:56:57.900 --> 00:56:59.360
There is gas.

00:56:59.360 --> 00:57:01.850
There's coalbed methane.

00:57:01.850 --> 00:57:07.850
There is some joint
occurrence of gas and coal.

00:57:07.850 --> 00:57:11.420
Historically, coal
companies ignored it,

00:57:11.420 --> 00:57:13.470
because it's a little
tricky to recover.

00:57:13.470 --> 00:57:17.690
There's more recovery
now of coalbed methane.

00:57:17.690 --> 00:57:24.020
And the percentages differ
a lot from place to place--

00:57:24.020 --> 00:57:24.980
oil versus gas.

00:57:24.980 --> 00:57:27.260
In Qatar, for instance,
it's almost all gas.

00:57:27.260 --> 00:57:29.105
In some places it's
almost all oil.

00:57:29.105 --> 00:57:30.980
But there tends to be--
well, the Middle East

00:57:30.980 --> 00:57:32.220
has lots of both.

00:57:32.220 --> 00:57:35.900
So in that broad sense,
that they co-locate.

00:57:35.900 --> 00:57:37.400
Yeah, Andrew.

00:57:37.400 --> 00:57:38.400
AUDIENCE: Two questions.

00:57:38.400 --> 00:57:41.480
One thing that you mentioned
was about the price.

00:57:41.480 --> 00:57:45.830
Does it track, or did it
used to track oil price

00:57:45.830 --> 00:57:47.000
at all, natural gas, I mean?

00:57:47.000 --> 00:57:48.958
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Yeah, that's a good point.

00:57:48.958 --> 00:57:50.240
It doesn't here.

00:57:50.240 --> 00:57:57.420
Back in the day when oil was
used to generate electricity,

00:57:57.420 --> 00:58:03.390
you had so-called "substitution"
at the burner tip,

00:58:03.390 --> 00:58:07.410
that the ability of power plants
to switch between natural gas

00:58:07.410 --> 00:58:11.520
and oil tended to link
their prices pretty tightly.

00:58:11.520 --> 00:58:13.800
The Russian price to Europe--

00:58:17.180 --> 00:58:20.270
prices, since it's not just one
price-- but the Russian prices

00:58:20.270 --> 00:58:25.100
to Europe tend to be linked
by contract to the oil price.

00:58:25.100 --> 00:58:29.750
In the US, since we
don't generate much--

00:58:29.750 --> 00:58:33.410
we don't effectively know
electricity from oil--

00:58:33.410 --> 00:58:38.210
there's some, but it's
not much, old diesels--

00:58:38.210 --> 00:58:40.730
that burner tip
substitution doesn't link

00:58:40.730 --> 00:58:42.950
and there's no contractual link.

00:58:42.950 --> 00:58:48.320
Now, per unit of energy,
gas is enormously cheaper

00:58:48.320 --> 00:58:49.820
than oil in the US--

00:58:49.820 --> 00:58:51.380
enormously cheaper.

00:58:51.380 --> 00:58:54.520
I'm trying to
remember the ratio.

00:58:54.520 --> 00:58:55.450
Is it 10 to 1?

00:58:55.450 --> 00:58:57.320
It can't be that high,
but it's pretty high.

00:58:57.320 --> 00:58:58.640
It's a big difference.

00:58:58.640 --> 00:59:00.700
So even if you could burn
oil in a power plant,

00:59:00.700 --> 00:59:04.113
you wouldn't today.

00:59:04.113 --> 00:59:06.280
And you haven't for a long
time because of the price

00:59:06.280 --> 00:59:07.003
difference.

00:59:07.003 --> 00:59:08.420
AUDIENCE: The other
question would

00:59:08.420 --> 00:59:12.650
be [INAUDIBLE] you mentioned
that there is no world

00:59:12.650 --> 00:59:14.470
market for natural gas.

00:59:14.470 --> 00:59:17.530
And I'm just
wondering, and I was

00:59:17.530 --> 00:59:20.770
going to mention that people
link it to oil, which doesn't

00:59:20.770 --> 00:59:22.790
make a lot of sense to me.

00:59:22.790 --> 00:59:24.910
I was wondering, and
you mentioned something

00:59:24.910 --> 00:59:26.920
that it's about--

00:59:26.920 --> 00:59:29.500
we might see a world
market for natural gas.

00:59:29.500 --> 00:59:32.470
What are the reasons that
they have not [INAUDIBLE]??

00:59:32.470 --> 00:59:34.220
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Cost, transport cost.

00:59:34.220 --> 00:59:37.330
AUDIENCE: Because I would
assume just because you have--

00:59:37.330 --> 00:59:39.905
the technology is there and
you see the differences--

00:59:39.905 --> 00:59:41.530
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Oh, the technology

00:59:41.530 --> 00:59:44.410
is there, but to
liquefy the gas--

00:59:44.410 --> 00:59:47.800
to compress it and
liquefy it costs money.

00:59:47.800 --> 00:59:49.760
The tankers are expensive.

00:59:49.760 --> 00:59:52.210
The terminal facilities
are expensive.

00:59:52.210 --> 00:59:55.090
So that's the reason why--

00:59:55.090 --> 00:59:58.240
Japan can import lots of gas,
but it's not a world market

00:59:58.240 --> 01:00:00.760
in the sense of a world price.

01:00:00.760 --> 01:00:04.160
Because the market has been
traditionally very different

01:00:04.160 --> 01:00:04.660
from the--

01:00:04.660 --> 01:00:08.770
North America is pipelines,
boom, boom, boom.

01:00:08.770 --> 01:00:11.020
And that's pretty unified.

01:00:11.020 --> 01:00:13.780
Pipelines are pretty cheap--

01:00:13.780 --> 01:00:16.250
all things equal,
pipelines are pretty cheap.

01:00:16.250 --> 01:00:19.030
But liquefying the stuff,
and putting it on board ship,

01:00:19.030 --> 01:00:24.220
and moving it across the ocean
is an expensive proposition,

01:00:24.220 --> 01:00:26.500
which is why the Asian
price has been so much

01:00:26.500 --> 01:00:28.780
higher than the European price.

01:00:28.780 --> 01:00:36.940
Now, as people say, suppose the
US really produces this stuff

01:00:36.940 --> 01:00:43.180
at scale and begins to
export in quantity to Asia

01:00:43.180 --> 01:00:46.840
to take into account
that price difference.

01:00:46.840 --> 01:00:49.240
Just geographically,
we're in a position

01:00:49.240 --> 01:00:52.090
to undermine Russian
pricing to Europe

01:00:52.090 --> 01:00:57.580
and in a position to undercut
Middle Eastern pricing to Asia.

01:00:57.580 --> 01:00:59.680
We don't have that
much gas, but we

01:00:59.680 --> 01:01:04.840
have enough, some people
argue, to unify the world

01:01:04.840 --> 01:01:06.400
in price terms.

01:01:06.400 --> 01:01:08.530
Some people say that's nuts.

01:01:08.530 --> 01:01:12.670
So it comes down to the numbers,
and how much we produce,

01:01:12.670 --> 01:01:14.830
and is there gas in China.

01:01:14.830 --> 01:01:19.500
If there's a lot
of gas in China,

01:01:19.500 --> 01:01:21.960
at cost comparable
to ours, then you

01:01:21.960 --> 01:01:25.890
begin to see world gas
prices of around $5 to $6

01:01:25.890 --> 01:01:29.760
instead of these $12,
$13, $14 prices in Asia.

01:01:33.360 --> 01:01:36.300
There's a possibility, but it's
not going to happen through--

01:01:36.300 --> 01:01:41.400
well, it can happen through
LNG, but it is expensive.

01:01:41.400 --> 01:01:43.480
It is expensive.

01:01:43.480 --> 01:01:44.700
Yeah.

01:01:44.700 --> 01:01:45.590
[INAUDIBLE]

01:01:45.590 --> 01:01:47.820
AUDIENCE: What's the carbon
intensity vis-a-vis oil?

01:01:47.820 --> 01:01:49.046
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Excuse me, what?

01:01:49.046 --> 01:01:51.420
AUDIENCE: What's the carbon
intensity vis-a-vis oil?

01:01:55.750 --> 01:01:59.290
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: It's less
carbon intensive than oil.

01:01:59.290 --> 01:02:00.040
It's methane.

01:02:00.040 --> 01:02:01.780
It's CH4.

01:02:01.780 --> 01:02:03.400
Oil tends to have
a good deal more.

01:02:03.400 --> 01:02:04.840
Oil varies.

01:02:04.840 --> 01:02:06.100
I can't give you a ratio.

01:02:06.100 --> 01:02:08.170
I should be able
to, but I can't.

01:02:08.170 --> 01:02:09.880
You can look it up.

01:02:09.880 --> 01:02:17.530
But it's about-- the one number
that it does stick in my head

01:02:17.530 --> 01:02:20.620
and this is because it's
a power plant number--

01:02:20.620 --> 01:02:24.790
using natural gas in a power
plant as compared to coal

01:02:24.790 --> 01:02:29.480
gives you about half
the CO2 emissions.

01:02:29.480 --> 01:02:32.540
Oil will be somewhere in
between, and different grades--

01:02:32.540 --> 01:02:35.120
Canadian heavy oil may
be more carbon intensive

01:02:35.120 --> 01:02:37.370
than light crude
from Saudi Arabia.

01:02:37.370 --> 01:02:41.197
I just don't know the answer,
but somewhere in between.

01:02:41.197 --> 01:02:41.780
Anything else?

01:02:41.780 --> 01:02:42.710
Prosper?

01:02:42.710 --> 01:02:45.350
AUDIENCE: Is coal
gas still being

01:02:45.350 --> 01:02:48.080
purchased internationally?

01:02:48.080 --> 01:02:52.070
Also, are there countries
where using coal gas

01:02:52.070 --> 01:02:53.432
is more cheaper than importing--

01:02:53.432 --> 01:02:54.890
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Importing LNG?

01:02:54.890 --> 01:02:55.890
AUDIENCE: --natural gas?

01:03:01.470 --> 01:03:02.980
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
I hate to admit

01:03:02.980 --> 01:03:04.970
that there's something
I completely don't know,

01:03:04.970 --> 01:03:06.380
but I don't know.

01:03:06.380 --> 01:03:09.350
It wouldn't surprise me.

01:03:09.350 --> 01:03:15.140
If a country has coal
supplies, doesn't have gas,

01:03:15.140 --> 01:03:17.780
and doesn't have
good port facilities,

01:03:17.780 --> 01:03:21.800
then it would make sense
to do coal gasification.

01:03:21.800 --> 01:03:25.820
There are places where--

01:03:25.820 --> 01:03:28.040
again, much of it's done--

01:03:28.040 --> 01:03:32.570
there's talk of and some
use of gas from coal

01:03:32.570 --> 01:03:36.860
to burn in power plants because
you're basically leaving

01:03:36.860 --> 01:03:38.370
some of the carbon behind.

01:03:38.370 --> 01:03:43.370
So you're getting combined
cycle efficiency, less carbon

01:03:43.370 --> 01:03:44.000
emissions.

01:03:47.400 --> 01:03:53.720
But whether it's in use
at scale, I don't know.

01:03:53.720 --> 01:03:56.860
The South Africans were doing--

01:03:56.860 --> 01:03:58.630
they were mostly
