01:04:21.860 --> 01:04:23.840
or is it for use in gas?

01:04:23.840 --> 01:04:25.790
AUDIENCE: Right now,
most of [INAUDIBLE]

01:04:25.790 --> 01:04:29.600
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Yeah,
electricity, so yeah, I

01:04:29.600 --> 01:04:32.720
can't rule out it being
put in pipes for heating

01:04:32.720 --> 01:04:36.120
and lighting someplace, but
I don't know of any place.

01:04:36.120 --> 01:04:37.330
Interesting question.

01:04:37.330 --> 01:04:38.340
Yeah.

01:04:38.340 --> 01:04:39.850
Anything else?

01:04:39.850 --> 01:04:42.100
Yeah, Ryan.

01:04:42.100 --> 01:04:46.330
AUDIENCE: So natural gas might
replace some coal because it's

01:04:46.330 --> 01:04:47.510
cheaper, in some instances.

01:04:47.510 --> 01:04:51.190
Will it replace oil in
a transportation sector

01:04:51.190 --> 01:04:54.220
or is that just out of
the question for a while?

01:04:54.220 --> 01:04:57.740
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Well,
that's a good question.

01:04:57.740 --> 01:05:00.430
One of the optional
readings for Wednesday

01:05:00.430 --> 01:05:03.530
is this MIT Future
of Natural Gas Study.

01:05:03.530 --> 01:05:08.150
And one of the things they
investigate is exactly that.

01:05:08.150 --> 01:05:13.320
If you think about one
of the issues that arises

01:05:13.320 --> 01:05:15.450
is energy density.

01:05:15.450 --> 01:05:17.940
Gasoline is just
this marvelous stuff

01:05:17.940 --> 01:05:20.700
because in a
relatively small space,

01:05:20.700 --> 01:05:25.710
you could store enough
energy to move a ton

01:05:25.710 --> 01:05:28.110
and a half vehicle 200 miles.

01:05:28.110 --> 01:05:34.350
Gas is hard to get that kind of
density unless you liquefy it.

01:05:34.350 --> 01:05:35.850
If you liquefy it,
of course, you've

01:05:35.850 --> 01:05:38.550
got all this problem
of keeping it cold

01:05:38.550 --> 01:05:40.940
and keeping the pressure.

01:05:40.940 --> 01:05:48.170
So on the other hand, per BTU,
it's so much cheaper than oil,

01:05:48.170 --> 01:05:50.330
than gasoline or diesel.

01:05:50.330 --> 01:05:54.170
So there's a lot of discussion.

01:05:54.170 --> 01:05:57.350
We will probably see,
assuming prices hold,

01:05:57.350 --> 01:06:01.070
we'll probably see a lot of
use of gas in urban fleets.

01:06:01.070 --> 01:06:06.380
You already see some, because a
bus fleet or a taxi fleet where

01:06:06.380 --> 01:06:08.870
you don't have to travel far
from a place you can refuel,

01:06:08.870 --> 01:06:10.370
you refuel often.

01:06:10.370 --> 01:06:13.430
And it's worth it if it's
just a whole lot cheaper

01:06:13.430 --> 01:06:17.080
to refuel a couple of
times a day to save money.

01:06:20.360 --> 01:06:23.180
There are no technical
problems building engines

01:06:23.180 --> 01:06:24.350
to run on the stuff.

01:06:24.350 --> 01:06:25.370
That happens now.

01:06:25.370 --> 01:06:28.880
You can buy cars that
can run on natural gas.

01:06:28.880 --> 01:06:30.950
It's just the refueling
infrastructure

01:06:30.950 --> 01:06:35.000
and the cruising range
is a problem for cars.

01:06:35.000 --> 01:06:36.140
People are talking.

01:06:36.140 --> 01:06:40.940
So urban fleets, yeah, delivery
vehicles, yeah, taxi cabs,

01:06:40.940 --> 01:06:42.080
yeah.

01:06:42.080 --> 01:06:45.230
There's talk about using
liquefied natural gas

01:06:45.230 --> 01:06:50.290
for long-haul trucks where
you don't need that many

01:06:50.290 --> 01:06:51.610
fueling stations.

01:06:51.610 --> 01:06:53.788
You need them on
the main routes.

01:06:53.788 --> 01:06:56.080
So instead of having to have
them all over the country,

01:06:56.080 --> 01:06:59.420
you can have a few
at certain intervals.

01:06:59.420 --> 01:07:01.750
And because you're
hauling a lot,

01:07:01.750 --> 01:07:06.940
it may be worthwhile to put
all that stuff on a truck.

01:07:10.080 --> 01:07:12.695
Again, the world divides
into those people

01:07:12.695 --> 01:07:15.070
who think it's the natural
next step and those people who

01:07:15.070 --> 01:07:16.690
think that's crazy.

01:07:16.690 --> 01:07:18.370
And I don't know the answer.

01:07:18.370 --> 01:07:19.610
